## **Hard Margin SVM vs. Soft Margin SVM**

### **Hard Margin SVM**
- **Assumes data is perfectly linearly separable.**
- **No misclassifications are allowed** — all data points must be correctly classified and lie outside (or on) the margin boundaries.
- **Objective:** Maximize the margin **strictly** with zero tolerance for errors.
- **Sensitive to outliers** — a single outlier can severely distort the hyperplane.
- **Only works when data is linearly separable.**

### **Soft Margin SVM**
- **Allows some misclassifications** — introduces slack variables to permit points to fall within or on the wrong side of the margin.
- **Objective:** Balance **margin maximization** and **minimizing classification errors** (controlled by a regularization parameter **C**).
- **More flexible** — handles noisy data and non-linearly separable cases.
- **Parameter C:**
  - **Large C:** Penalizes misclassifications heavily → closer to hard margin.
  - **Small C:** Allows more misclassifications → wider margin, more robust to outliers.

---

## **Key Difference**

| Aspect | Hard Margin | Soft Margin |
|---|---|---|
| Misclassifications | Not allowed | Allowed (controlled by C) |
| Data separability | Must be linearly separable | Works even if not perfectly separable |
| Outlier sensitivity | High | Lower |
| Regularization | None | Controlled by parameter C |

---

## **When to Use Which?**

- **Hard margin:** Rarely used in practice — only when data is clean and perfectly separable.
- **Soft margin:** The standard approach in real-world applications where data contains noise and outliers.

